\u003cp\u003eThere is a way to play the \u003cem\u003ePokémon\u003c/em\u003e \u003cem\u003eTCG\u003c/em\u003e on your phone or tablet that is entirely free. Not “free-to-play,” but “free to leave it with your kid and not ever worry.” While it’s not the world’s best piece of software, \u003cspan\u003e\u003ca data-ga=\"[[\u0026#34;Embedded Url\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;External link\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;https://tcg.pokemon.com/en-gb/tcgl/\u0026#34;,{\u0026#34;metric25\u0026#34;:1}]]\" href=\"https://tcg.pokemon.com/en-gb/tcgl/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"\u003e\u003cem\u003ePokémon\u003c/em\u003e \u003cem\u003eTCG Live\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e is an application that lets you play the full-size, 60-card deck version of the trading card game for an unlimited amount of time and doesn’t feature a single way to pay money. Cards are added to the game using the code cards that come as an extra in physical \u003cem\u003ePokémon\u003c/em\u003e card packs, but they can also be bought in their hundreds for cents from various websites and stores (I throw them in the recycling in stacks), but that’s the end of any expenses. Even if you wanted to, there’s no way to add your bank card to purchase even the silliest of cosmetics. And when it comes to \u003cem\u003ePokémon\u003c/em\u003e, that feels \u003cem\u003eright\u003c/em\u003e. — John Walker\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003e\u003ca data-ga=\"[[\u0026#34;Embedded Url\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;Internal link\u0026#34;,\u0026#34;https://kotaku.com/pokemon-tcg-pocket-gacha-loot-box-gambling-1851690838\u0026#34;,{\u0026#34;metric25\u0026#34;:1}]]\" href=\"https://kotaku.com/pokemon-tcg-pocket-gacha-loot-box-gambling-1851690838\"\u003eRead More\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cfigure id=\"\" data-id=\"397faccc92a7148c6ddccef8ad658e85\" data-recommend-id=\"image://397faccc92a7148c6ddccef8ad658e85\" data-format=\"jpg\" data-width=\"1741\" 